  accentWord="Glazing Contractor"
  subhead="Your latest reel is a thirty-second reveal of a structural glass balustrade on a first-floor terrace — the final panel being lowered into the base channel, silicone applied, the stainless steel handrail clicked into place, and the camera pulling back to show the full terrace with an unobstructed panoramic view over the Oxfordshire countryside. Fifty-five thousand views. A homeowner in Cumnor DMs: 'We are building a first-floor balcony on our extension and want a balustrade exactly like that. How do we get started?' You are on site fitting sealed units in a new-build. Without AI DMs, the message waits. With it, she shares a photo of the balcony steel frame, and your lead is captured with dimensions and photo."
  scenario="It is 11:30pm on a Friday. A young couple in Kidlington have been scrolling through glazing contractors on Instagram, looking for someone to replace the windows in their 1930s semi — six timber sash windows with single glazing, draughty in winter and noisy from the road. They want to keep the original sash style but with double-glazed slim-profile sealed units and draught-proofing. They find your account and see a carousel of heritage sash window upgrades — single-glazed originals replaced with slim double-glazed units, the sash profiles preserved, the condensation eliminated. She DMs: 'We have six single-glazed timber sash windows in our 1930s semi. They are draughty and noisy. We want to keep the sash style but upgrade to double glazing. Can you just change the glass or do we need new windows? OX5 area. Budget is flexible — we just want it done properly.' Without AI Instagram DMs, you see the DM Saturday morning. She has also DM'd two other glaziers; one responded at 11:45pm with a clear explanation of slim-profile sealed unit retrofitting and an offer of a free survey. With AI DMs, the reply arrives at 11:31pm: 'Thank you — heritage sash window upgrades with slim-profile double-glazed units are one of our specialisms. In most cases, the original sash boxes are retained and only the glass and putty are replaced. Could you share photos of the current windows and confirm the approximate pane sizes? We will arrange a survey to assess the sash condition and recommend the best approach.' She sends four photos — front elevation, close-up of the glazing bars, the draughty bottom rail, and the rear sash. Saturday at 9am you open the lead: 1930s semi, OX5, six timber sash windows, single-glazed to slim DG upgrade, draught and noise issues, heritage style preservation, photos attached, flexible budget. You call at 10am and book a Tuesday evening survey."
